value.value: A seizure occurring in infants and young children that occurs in the setting of fever.

An imaging technique that uses multiple photons to absorb infrared light, thereby minimizing phototoxicty and photobleaching, making it an ideal method for imaging living specimens, especially those involving deep tissue.
A diagnostic tool used to view tissues at high magnification, which allows for identification of cellular structures.

An operative technique that uses real time correlation of the operative field with preoperative images in order to establish the precise location of surgical instruments in relation to surrounding anatomical structures.
An image-guided, minimally invasive surgical technique that uses a probe inserted through the skin to freeze the targeted tissue, causing cell death secondary to cryogenic injury.
A surgical technique that uses a specially designed robotic system to aid with an endoscopic procedure.
A surgical technique that uses a specially designed robotic system to aid with a laparoscopic surgical procedure.
A diagnostic procedure that uses an ultrasound image to guide the placement of a biopsy needle into the prostate to obtain a tissue sample.
A radiologic technique that employs contrast agents to enable a more precise needle placement during a biopsy of the prostate.

label.value: Endoscopic Ultrasound-Guided Fine-Needle Aspiration of the Pancreas

value.value: The use of endoscopic ultrasound to direct the placement of a needle being used to obtain a sample of cells from the pancreas. The use of the ultrasound allows for more precise needle placement and makes the procedure safer.

A treatment that involves injection of local anesthetic and alcohol to the celiac plexus, causing temporary degeneration of the nerve fibers. The procedure is performed in an effort to alleviate intractable pain, generally caused by cancer or chronic pancreatitis.

The use of endoscopic ultrasound to guide the injection of local anesthetic and alcohol to the celiac plexus, which causes temporary degeneration to the nerve fibers. The procedure is performed in an effort to alleviate intractable plain, generally caused by cancer or chronic pancreatitis.
Any test performed on air generated by the act of exhaling.
A diagnostic test that measures the amount of nitric oxide in an exhaled breath.
A clinical tool to evaluate exercise capacity and to assess cardiac function under stress.
Interventions or procedures not otherwise categorized.
A set of therapy techniques derived from the school of cognitive psychology, which the practitioner uses to conduct therapy.

An act of intercession by an outside party for the purpose of clarifying or improving the exchange of information between individuals, such as between physician and patient or by an individual with a communication disorder.
The use of a computer to facilitate the processing of complex information, and then aiding in the creation and execution of a plan of action based on that information.
Any program that uses the internet to alter, modify, or eliminate a behavior.
Any intervention or procedure performed by a caregiver during the course of their duties.
The use of a computer for the creation and execution of a plan to help an individual stop smoking.
An act of intercession or assistance for an individual that is performed by their caregiver.
Any action taken for the purpose of improving an individual's memory.

A procedure that functions as the control arm of a clinical trial, mimicking the procedure under investigation in every way, including the preprocedure routine, anaesthesia and incisions (if necessary), and post-procedure follow-up, without actually providing or performing the procedure being studied.
Any program that uses interactions over the telephone to alter, modify, or eliminate an undesired behavior.
Seizures in the first years of life characterized by flexion and extension jerks of the neck, trunk, and extremities.
Any focused education provided to a caregiver.
The attempt to improve the techniques and tactics an individual uses to communicate.
The use of a computer to help an individual improve cognitive skills including focus, attention, memory, and information processing.
Any program that aims to teach the partner or caregiver of a patient a specific set of skills intended to help relieve the physical, emotional, and/or mental stress experienced by the patient.
The use of EGFR tyrosine kinase inhibitors to disrupt the activation of EGFR, effectively halting the signaling cascade for cell growth, thereby decreasing tumor proliferation and migration.
The use of external electrical current to stimulate nerves for the purpose of reducing pain.
The use of an external electrical field to facilitate the transfer of a plasmid into a cell for the purpose of introducing genetically modified DNA and stimulating a immunological response.
The administration of fluids, most commonly via an intravenous route, to restore intravascular volume.
A neurological disorder of childhood characterized by partial seizures consisting of twitching, numbness, or tingling of the face or tongue that often progress to secondary generalized seizures.
A type of immunotherapy in which tumor cells have been modified to make them more immunogenic, thereby activating the immune system to attack and destroy the tumor.
Any treatment modality that exercises its effects by inducing, enhancing, or suppressing an immune response.
A technique used to improve the efficacy of radioimmunotherapy that targets the tumor with both an antibody construct and a radiolabeled hapten prior to the administration of radiation therapy.
A method of delivering internal beam radiotherapy that involves delivering short bursts of radiation over a specified period of time.
The administration of exogenous hormones via bolus injection into the tissue layer immediately deep to the dermis.
A type of immunotherapy that uses a synthetic peptide to deliver tumor-specific antigens into the body in an effort to induce a targeted immune system response directed at the tumor.
The application of steroid medications to the skin for the treatment of various conditions.
A method by which dendritic cells are pulsed in vitro with tumor cell lysate to induce maturation with the purpose of inducing a targeted immune system response against the tumor.

A method of intraoperative blood conservation in which whole blood is drained by gravity into a collection bag where it is mixed with anticoagulants and maintained at room temperature. As the blood is collected, an intravenous fluid is infused to maintain normal blood volume. The collected blood can be transfused to the patient during and/or after surgery as needed.
Movements, behaviors and sensations similar to a seizure, but due to psychological distress instead of a neurological disorder.
